    color: '#C0392B',
    narrative: `Rome did not begin as an empire — it began as a city of seven hills, a republic built on the radical idea that power could be shared. For five centuries, consuls and senators governed, armies conquered, and Rome grew until the republic itself cracked under the weight of its own ambition. Julius Caesar crossed the Rubicon. His heir Augustus did something more lasting: he kept the forms of the republic while hollowing them out, becoming the first emperor in all but name.\n\nAt its height under Trajan in 117 AD, the Roman Empire stretched from Scotland to Mesopotamia, governing some 70 million people — a fifth of all humanity. It was not just military might that held this together. Rome gave its subjects roads, aqueducts, courts, and a shared language. Merchants in Alexandria and soldiers in Britain both spoke Latin, both carried Roman coins, both lived under Roman law. The empire was, in many ways, the world's first experiment in globalization.\n\nThe fall was not a single catastrophe but a long unraveling — barbarian migrations, economic strain, military overspend, and religious transformation all played their part. By 476 AD, the last western emperor was deposed not with a battle but with a shrug. Yet Rome never truly died. Its language became French, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, and Romanian. Its law became the foundation of every Western legal system. Its church became the Catholic Church. We still live inside the skeleton of Rome.`,
