    narrative: `The Nile made Egypt possible. Every year the river flooded, retreated, and left behind rich black silt — kemet, the Egyptians called it, "the black land" — and this predictable miracle allowed a civilization to take root and hold for thirty centuries without fundamental interruption. No other civilization in history has maintained a recognizable cultural identity for so long. Dynasties rose and fell, foreign powers invaded, but Egypt endured.\n\nWhat the pharaohs built with that stability was staggering. The Great Pyramid of Giza was raised around 2560 BC and remained the tallest human-made structure on Earth for nearly four thousand years. The Egyptians did not build in stone merely to impress — they built for eternity, because eternity was the central preoccupation of their entire civilization. Death was not an end but a passage, and the resources of an entire nation were organized around preparing the pharaoh for what came next.\n\nBeyond the monuments, Egypt gave the world writing, medicine, mathematics, and the 365-day calendar. Its culture so captivated the ancient world that conquerors — Persians, Greeks, Romans — all became Egyptianized rather than erasing what they found. When Cleopatra VII died in 30 BC and Egypt became a Roman province, the world lost something irreplaceable: the last living thread of an unbroken tradition stretching back to the very dawn of recorded history.`,
