    narrative: `China had been united by force under the brutal Qin Dynasty, but it was the Han who taught it how to stay together. Liu Bang, a peasant who rose to become emperor, established a dynasty that would last four centuries and define what it meant to be Chinese. Even today, the majority ethnic group of China calls itself the Han people — not after the Qin who first united the country, but after the dynasty that gave unity a soul.\n\nThe genius of the Han was the civil service. Rather than relying solely on aristocratic birth or military loyalty, the Han instituted examinations that anyone, in theory, could pass. This meritocratic idea — that the best-qualified should govern — was radical and world-historical. It created a class of educated administrators who held the empire together across centuries and was the foundation of Chinese governance for two thousand years.\n\nUnder Emperor Wu, Han armies pushed deep into Central Asia, and with them went silk, spices, and ideas. The trade routes that came to be called the Silk Road opened the ancient world's first long-distance cultural exchange, connecting China to Persia, Rome, and India. Paper was invented. Seismographs were built. The Han gave China its script, its philosophy, its sense of civilizational purpose — and the world a route by which every great idea could travel.`,
