    narrative: `When Spanish conquistadors first glimpsed Tenochtitlan in 1519, they could not believe what they were seeing. Hernán Cortés wrote to the Spanish king that this island city in the middle of a lake was larger and more beautiful than any city in Spain. Its causeways, temples, markets, and aqueducts rivaled anything in Europe — and the Aztecs had built it all in less than two centuries, rising from a wandering tribe to the masters of Mesoamerica.\n\nThe Aztecs called themselves the Mexica, and their empire was held together not by direct conquest but by a sophisticated system of tribute and alliance. Subject peoples paid in goods — maize, cacao, textiles, jade — and in return received the Aztec order: markets that functioned, roads that connected, and the terrifying assurance that the sun would continue to rise. Because the Aztecs genuinely believed that without ritual sacrifice, the sun would fail — and the whole cosmic machinery of the universe would grind to a halt.\n\nThis was not mere superstition but the operating logic of an entire civilization. Their calendars were instruments of extraordinary precision. Their city was a feat of hydraulic engineering. Their poets wrote with a melancholy beauty that still stuns translators. When Tenochtitlan fell to Cortés in 1521 — aided by smallpox and a coalition of peoples who resented Aztec dominance — it was not a triumph of civilization over barbarism. It was the destruction of one of the most remarkable cities the ancient Americas ever produced.`,
