    narrative: `For six hundred years, the Ottoman Empire was the hinge of the world — the power that sat between Europe and Asia, between Christendom and Islam, controlling the trade routes that made the Mediterranean make sense. It began as a small Anatolian principality founded by a warrior chief named Osman, and it ended as a multi-continental empire whose collapse created the modern Middle East and reshaped Europe forever.\n\nThe moment that defined the empire came in 1453, when the twenty-one-year-old Sultan Mehmed II did what no one had managed in a thousand years: he took Constantinople. The city that had been the capital of the Byzantine Empire, guardian of Roman civilization's eastern branch, fell in fifty-three days. Mehmed rode into the Hagia Sophia and declared it a mosque. The medieval world was over.\n\nAt its peak under Suleiman the Magnificent, the empire governed thirty-five million people across three continents, its treasury overflowing, its architecture sublime, its law sophisticated. The Millet system allowed Christians, Jews, and Muslims to live under their own religious courts — a pragmatic pluralism that held the empire together but also kept its peoples divided. When the empire finally dissolved after the First World War, the lines drawn to replace it — artificial borders, arbitrary states — produced a century of conflict that has never fully resolved.`,
