    narrative: `Genghis Khan came from nothing. Born into a minor clan, kidnapped as a child, abandoned by allies, he built the largest contiguous empire in human history through a combination of military genius, political cunning, and an almost supernatural ability to inspire loyalty in men who had every reason to kill him. By the time he died in 1227, his armies had conquered territory from the Pacific Ocean to the Caspian Sea — and his generals were just getting started.\n\nThe secret of Mongol conquest was not simply violence, though the violence was real and catastrophic. It was speed, information, and meritocracy. Mongol armies moved faster than any force their enemies had encountered, communicating through relay riders, absorbing the best engineers from every civilization they conquered. Generals were promoted by ability, not birth. Cities that surrendered were spared. Cities that resisted were erased as warnings. It was a brutal rational system — and it worked.\n\nThe Pax Mongolica that followed conquest was, paradoxically, one of history's great periods of globalization. For the first time, a merchant could travel safely from Venice to Beijing. Ideas, technologies, and diseases moved along these routes — the Black Death likely traveled west along the Mongol trade corridors. When the empire fragmented and then collapsed, it left behind successor states from China to Persia, and a memory so formidable that rulers from India to Russia would claim Mongol descent for centuries as a mark of legitimacy.`,
