    narrative: `Ancient Greece was never a single nation — it was a collection of fiercely independent city-states, often at war with each other, united only by a shared language, shared gods, and a shared conviction that the examined life was the only life worth living. Out of this fractious, competitive, endlessly arguing world came democracy, philosophy, tragedy, comedy, history as a discipline, and the foundational texts of Western science.\n\nAthens in the fifth century BC was something extraordinary: a city of perhaps 300,000 people that somehow produced Socrates, Plato, Aristotle, Aeschylus, Sophocles, Euripides, Thucydides, and Herodotus within a single century. These were not isolated geniuses — they were the product of a culture that valued public debate, questioning authority, and the relentless pursuit of truth. The agora, the public square where Athenians argued and philosophized, was not just an institution — it was a way of life.\n\nThe great tragedy of ancient Greece was that it destroyed itself. Athens and Sparta bled each other white in the Peloponnesian War, and when Philip of Macedon swept down from the north, there was nothing left to resist. His son Alexander spread Greek culture from Egypt to India, but the living polis — the citizen-governed city — was finished. Greece became a province of Rome. But Greek ideas never died. They traveled through Rome, through Islamic scholars, through the Renaissance, and form the core of how the modern world thinks about politics, ethics, beauty, and truth.`,
