    narrative: `India had seen kingdoms and confederacies, but it had never seen anything like the Maurya Empire. Chandragupta Maurya, guided by the ruthless political genius of his advisor Kautilya — whose treatise on statecraft, the Arthashastra, would not be out of place in a modern political science course — built the first state to control nearly the entire Indian subcontinent. He did it at the age of roughly twenty, defeating the remnants of Alexander the Great's empire as he went.\n\nBut the figure who made the Maurya Empire immortal was Chandragupta's grandson Ashoka. He inherited a conquering empire and expanded it further, until the Kalinga War of 261 BC confronted him with the full horror of what conquest meant — 100,000 dead, hundreds of thousands displaced. Ashoka was transformed. He converted to Buddhism, renounced offensive war, and did something no ruler in history had done before: he inscribed his new ethical code on rocks and pillars across his entire empire, making his remorse and his commitments public.\n\nThese Edicts of Ashoka are the world's first known public declarations of a ruler's obligations to his people — promoting religious tolerance, animal welfare, medical care, and just governance. They predate the Magna Carta by 1,500 years. When the empire collapsed after Ashoka's death, it left behind an idea that has never entirely faded: that power has moral obligations.`,
