    color: '#16A085',
    narrative: `The Inca built an empire in the most hostile terrain on Earth. The Andes are not gentle mountains — they are brutal, high, cold, and fractured by deep gorges that should make large-scale civilization impossible. The Inca did not just survive this landscape; they mastered it. They cut terraces into vertical slopes to create farmland. They built suspension bridges across chasms. They strung a relay runner network across 40,000 kilometers of mountain road that could carry messages faster than any horse.\n\nAt its heart, the Inca Empire was a system of reciprocity. The state fed its people in return for labor — on roads, temples, armies, farms. There was no money, no markets in the Western sense; instead, an elaborate accounting system using knotted strings called quipus tracked every obligation, every allocation, every warehouse of stored food. It was, in some ways, the most sophisticated command economy the ancient world ever produced.\n\nMachu Picchu, built on a ridge above the clouds around 1450, is the empire's most famous image — but it is only one of hundreds of such sites scattered across the Andes. When Francisco Pizarro arrived in 1532, he found a civilization already weakened by civil war and smallpox. With 168 soldiers, he captured the Inca emperor Atahualpa, collected a roomful of gold as ransom, and then executed him anyway. The greatest empire the Americas had ever known fell not to superior civilization, but to disease, betrayal, and the shock of the utterly unexpected.`,
