    narrative: `When Rome fell in the West, it did not fall in the East. The Eastern Roman Empire — which we now call Byzantine — survived for another thousand years, governing from Constantinople, the city that Constantine had built on the strait between Europe and Asia. It outlasted the Western Roman Empire by nearly a millennium, preserving the laws, literature, and philosophy of the classical world through the Dark Ages that engulfed the West.\n\nThe Byzantines thought of themselves simply as Romans. They spoke Greek, but their emperor held the Roman title, their legal system was the Corpus Juris Civilis compiled under Justinian, and their greatest building — the Hagia Sophia, completed in 537 — was the largest domed structure in the world for nearly a thousand years. Standing inside it, early visitors reported, one could not tell whether it was suspended from heaven or resting on earth.\n\nFor centuries, Constantinople was the most sophisticated city in the Christian world — a million inhabitants, running water, public baths, libraries, and a tradition of theological debate so intense that a dispute about the divine nature of Christ could spark riots in the streets. When the city finally fell to Mehmed II's Ottoman forces in 1453, the scholars who fled carried with them manuscripts of Plato and Aristotle that would light the fuse of the Italian Renaissance. Even in its death, Byzantium gave the West its rebirth.`,
