    narrative: `Everything began here. Before Mesopotamia — before the land between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers — there were human beings, but there was no civilization as we understand it. No cities. No writing. No codified law. No organized religion with temples and priests. No wheeled carts, no sailing vessels, no mathematics beyond counting. In the river valleys of what is now southern Iraq, between roughly 4500 and 3000 BC, all of this was invented, more or less simultaneously, in what remains the most concentrated burst of human innovation in all of history.\n\nThe Sumerians built Uruk, the world's first true city, and within it arose the world's first bureaucracy — because a city requires record-keeping, and record-keeping requires writing. Cuneiform, pressed into wet clay tablets with a reed stylus, began as accounting: lists of grain, livestock, workers. But once you have a technology for recording, it becomes something more. The Epic of Gilgamesh — the story of a king who loses his closest friend and goes to the ends of the earth searching for immortality, only to learn that it cannot be found — was written in Sumerian around 2100 BC. It is the oldest story that survives. Its themes are timeless because they are ours.\n\nSumer itself was eventually absorbed into the Akkadian Empire, then the Babylonian. The Sumerian language ceased to be spoken. But Sumerian knowledge — its mathematics, its astronomy, its mythology — passed into every civilization that followed. The sixty seconds in a minute and the three hundred and sixty degrees in a circle: these are Sumerian ideas, still governing our world six thousand years later.`,
    legacy: 'Writing, the wheel, the sixty-minute hour, the 360-degree circle, organized religion, codified law, and the very concept of the city — all Sumerian inventions. Every civilization that followed, including our own, is built on the foundations they poured in the river mud.',
    achievements: [
      'Invented cuneiform, one of the earliest writing systems on Earth',
      'Built the first true cities, including Uruk — the world\'s first metropolis',
      'Developed the earliest known legal codes, preceding Hammurabi',
      'Created complex irrigation systems to farm the arid Mesopotamian plains',
      'Pioneered mathematics, including a base-60 number system still used for time',
      'Composed the Epic of Gilgamesh, the world\'s oldest surviving literary work',
    ],
