    tagline: "China's last imperial dynasty — a vast multiethnic empire brought low by modernity.",
    color: '#2C3E50',
    narrative: `The Qing were Manchu — outsiders from the northeast who swept into China in 1644 and conquered the greatest civilization on Earth. And then they did what every successful conqueror of China has done: they became Chinese. The Qing emperors learned Mandarin, mastered Confucian scholarship, patronized Chinese art, and governed through the existing Chinese bureaucracy. They were Manchu in court ceremony, Chinese in governance, and Mongol in their management of the Central Asian borderlands. The empire they built was the largest in Chinese history.\n\nAt its 18th-century peak under the Qianlong Emperor, the Qing governed 430 million people — roughly a third of all humanity. The emperor in 1793 famously dismissed a British trade mission, writing to King George III that China had no need for foreign goods: "Our Celestial Empire possesses all things in prolific abundance." It was not arrogance but the accumulated confidence of the world's oldest, largest, and most sophisticated civilization. It was also a catastrophic miscalculation about what the Industrial Revolution was about to change.\n\nThe Opium Wars of the mid-19th century shattered the Qing's self-image. British warships — steam-powered, iron-hulled, carrying weapons the Qing army could not match — forced China to accept the opium trade, cede Hong Kong, and open its ports. The century that followed is remembered in China as the "Century of Humiliation." When the last emperor, the six-year-old Puyi, abdicated in 1912, he ended not just a dynasty but four millennia of continuous imperial rule — the longest-running political tradition in human history.`,
