    tagline: "The empire that made Iran Shia — and Isfahan one of the world's most beautiful cities.",
    color: '#1ABC9C',
    narrative: `In 1501, a fourteen-year-old boy named Ismail led an army into Tabriz and declared himself Shah of Iran. Within a decade he had conquered nearly all of Persia. Within a generation, he had done something more consequential than conquest: he had made Iran Shia Muslim, converting a population that was largely Sunni by a combination of persuasion, coercion, and the simple power of making Shia the official state religion. That decision, made over five hundred years ago, is the reason Iran is Shia today — and the reason the Sunni-Shia divide in Islam runs precisely along the old Ottoman-Safavid border.\n\nThe Safavid Empire's greatest moment came under Shah Abbas I, who moved the capital to Isfahan in 1598 and spent the next thirty years turning it into one of the most beautiful cities the world has ever seen. The Imam Mosque, the Ali Qapu palace, the Sheikh Lotfollah Mosque, the magnificent bazaar — all arranged around the vast Naqsh-e Jahan Square, still one of the largest public squares on Earth. Abbas also reformed the army, replacing tribal levies with a professional force equipped with artillery and muskets, transforming Persia into a modern military power.\n\nPersian poetry, painting, carpet-weaving, and architecture reached their peak under Safavid patronage. The miniature paintings produced in Safavid workshops — intricate, jewel-like, impossibly detailed — are among the greatest achievements of Islamic art. When European visitors came to Isfahan, they described it with a word that became a proverb in Persian: "Isfahan is half the world."`,
    legacy: 'The Safavid decision to make Persia Shia Muslim is the single most consequential act in shaping the modern Middle East. Iran\'s national identity — Persian language, Shia Islam, a distinctive culture proudly different from its Arab neighbors — is a Safavid creation. Isfahan\'s architecture remains among the greatest in the world.',
