    peakPopulation: '~1 million',
    language: 'Meroitic / Egyptian',
    religion: 'Egyptian-influenced polytheism / Amon worship',
    tagline: 'The forgotten pharaohs — a civilization that once ruled Egypt itself.',
    color: '#D35400',
    narrative: `History has not been kind to Nubia. For most of Western scholarship's existence, the civilization that flourished for three thousand years along the Nile south of Egypt was treated as a footnote to Egyptian history — a source of gold, slaves, and exotic goods, not a civilization in its own right. This is one of history's great distortions. The Kingdom of Kush was, at various points, Egypt's rival, Egypt's conqueror, and Egypt's guardian — a civilization of comparable sophistication that built more pyramids than Egypt, traded across half of Africa, and ruled the Nile for a combined span longer than the Roman Empire.\n\nThe most dramatic moment in Nubian history came in the 8th century BC, when the Kushite king Piye swept north and conquered all of Egypt, establishing the 25th Dynasty — the "Black Pharaohs" who would rule the Nile Valley for nearly a century. These Kushite pharaohs were not conquerors who imposed their culture; they were devotees of Egyptian civilization who believed they were restoring it to its proper purity after a period of foreign interference and internal decay. They built temples in the Egyptian style, adopted Egyptian titles, and presented themselves as the legitimate heirs of three thousand years of pharaonic tradition.\n\nAfter the Assyrians expelled the Kushites from Egypt, the kingdom retreated south and eventually moved its capital to Meroë, where it continued to flourish for seven more centuries. The Meroitic script, developed there, has never been fully deciphered. The iron-working technology that Meroë exported helped transform sub-Saharan Africa. When the Kingdom of Aksum finally conquered Meroë around 350 AD, it ended a civilization whose full story we are only now beginning to recover.`,
    legacy: 'Over 200 Nubian pyramids still stand in Sudan — more than in Egypt. The 25th Dynasty\'s period of rule preserved and extended Egyptian cultural traditions at a moment when they might otherwise have been lost. Nubian iron technology was foundational to the development of sub-Saharan African civilization.',
