    language: 'Ancient Greek / Macedonian',
    religion: 'Greek Polytheism',
    tagline: 'The fastest empire ever built — conquered the known world in thirteen years.',
    color: '#3498DB',
    narrative: `Alexander the Great died at thirty-two, having conquered the known world. This is a sentence that requires a moment to absorb. In thirteen years of continuous campaign, beginning when he was twenty, Alexander defeated the Persian Empire — the largest empire that had ever existed — conquered Egypt and was declared a god, pushed east through Central Asia to the borders of India, defeated Indian war elephants in monsoon rain on the banks of the Hydaspes River, and was ultimately stopped not by any enemy but by his own homesick soldiers. He never lost a battle.\n\nThe military genius was real and staggering — Alexander's use of the Macedonian phalanx combined with devastating cavalry charges, his personal leadership from the front (he was wounded multiple times and nearly killed at least once), his ability to adapt his tactics to every new enemy he faced. But what made Alexander world-historical was not the conquering but what came after: the deliberate fusion of cultures. He married a Bactrian princess. He adopted Persian court dress and customs. He encouraged his officers to marry Persian women. He founded over twenty cities named Alexandria across three continents, staffed them with Greek settlers, and created the conditions for the Hellenistic world — a cultural synthesis of Greek, Persian, Egyptian, and Indian ideas that produced advances in science, philosophy, and art that the world would not surpass for a thousand years.\n\nWhen Alexander died in Babylon in 323 BC, his generals asked him who should inherit his empire. "To the strongest," he reportedly said. His generals spent the next forty years trying to kill each other, dividing his empire into successor kingdoms. But the Hellenistic world he created lasted until Rome absorbed it — and even then, it was Greek culture that conquered Rome in return.`,
    legacy: 'The Hellenistic civilization Alexander created — the blend of Greek philosophy and science with Persian, Egyptian, and Indian traditions — produced the Library of Alexandria, Euclidean geometry, Archimedes\' physics, and Hipparchus\' astronomy. Without Alexander, there may have been no scientific revolution. He also ensured that Greek became the common language in which the New Testament was written.',
